I cannot write the entire code for a Discord bot in this text response, but I can provide you with an outline and a basic example using Discord.js v14 for a slash command called `ban`. Please make sure you have Node.js installed and set up on your machine, and create a new project with `npm init -y` and install Discord.js with `npm install discord.js`. Then create a new file `index.js` and add the following code:

1. First, import the required modules:

```javascript
const { Client, Intents, SlashCommandBuilder } = require('discord.js');
```

2. Initialize the client with intents and create an instance of the SlashCommandBuilder for the ban command:

```javascript
const client = new Client({ intents: [Intents.FLAGS.Guilds, Intents.FLAGS.Bans, Intents.FLAGS.Messages] });
const banCommand = new SlashCommandBuilder()
  .setName('ban')
  .setDescription('Ban a user from the server')
  .addUserOption((option) => option.setName('user').setDescription('The user to ban').setRequired(true))
  .addStringOption((option) => option.setName('reason').setDescription('The reason for the ban').setOptional());
```

3. Register the ban command to the client and login:

```javascript
client.commands = new Map();
client.commands.set('ban', banCommand.toJSON());

client.on('interactionCreate', async (interaction) => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  const command = client.commands.get(interaction.commandName);
  if (!command) return;

  try {
    const user = interaction.options.getUser('user');
    const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason') || 'No reason provided';

    await interaction.guild.members.ban(user, { reason });

    interaction.reply(`User ${user.tag} has been banned. Reason: ${reason}`);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
    interaction.reply('An error occurred while trying to ban the user.');
  }
});

client.login('your-bot-token');
```

Replace `'your-bot-token'` with your bot's token. This example assumes you have the necessary permissions to ban users in the server where the command is used. Make sure to handle errors and edge cases appropriately in a production environment.

Keep in mind that this example does not include any error handling or configuration options. You should extend it according to your needs. For more information, refer to the official Discord.js documentation: https://discordjs.guide/slash-commands/intro.html.

To test your bot, invite it to a server and use the slash command with the given syntax: `/ban @UserMention [reason]`. Remember that bots must have the Manage Server or Ban Members permission to ban users.

