I'll write you a function named `checkPrimes` that takes an array of numbers as an argument, and filters out the prime numbers among them. Prime numbers are numbers greater than 1 that can only be divided evenly by 1 and themselves. This function will not directly print to the console inside itself for modularity, but instead return an array of prime numbers found, allowing you to later print it if desired.

```javascript
function isPrime(num) {
  if (num <= 1) return false; // Numbers 0 and negative numbers aren't prime
  for (let i = 2; i <= Math.sqrt(num); i++)
    if (num % i === 0) return false; // If divisible by any number up to its square root, it's not prime
  return true;
}

function checkPrimes(arr) {
  if (arr.length !== 5) throw new Error("Input array must contain exactly 5 numbers.");
  const primeNumbers = [];
  for (let num of arr) {
    if (isPrime(num)) primeNumbers.push(num);
  }
  console.log(primeNumbers); // Uncomment this line if you want to print the prime numbers to the console.
  return primeNumbers;
}
```

This `checkPrimes` function uses an inner helper function `isPrime` to determine whether a given number is prime or not. It checks for divisibility up to the square root of the number, as any factor larger than the square root would have a corresponding factor smaller than the square root with which it forms a perfect square. This optimization makes the prime check more efficient.

You can use this function as follows:

```javascript
checkPrimes([3, 5, 2, 6, 7]); // Output: [3, 5, 7] (when called with a valid array of length 5)
checkPrimes([1, 2, 3, 5, 7]); // Output: [2, 3, 5, 7] (when given an array containing prime numbers)
checkPrimes([1, 2, 3, 5, 8]); // Output: [2, 3, 5] (only prime numbers are collected and printed/returned)
checkPrimes([10, 9, 8, 7, 6]); // Error: Input array must contain exactly 5 numbers.
```

Keep in mind that the function will throw an error if the input array does not have a length of 5. You can modify the error message or remove it altogether if desired.

